Lorentz.

765
00:30:35,260 --> 00:30:36,860
L-O-R-E-N-T-Z.

766
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:39,160
The same gentleman who first wrote down

767
00:30:39,160 --> 00:30:40,020
the Lorentz transformations.

768
00:30:41,860 --> 00:30:42,380
Okay,

769
00:30:42,380 --> 00:30:42,640
so,

770
00:30:44,620 --> 00:30:46,720
this term is called the Lorentz force law.

771
00:30:48,160 --> 00:30:50,180
Let's check that this Lagrangian

772
00:30:50,180 --> 00:30:52,560
gives rise to Lorentz's equation of motion

773
00:30:52,560 --> 00:30:54,240
for the motion of a particle.

774
00:30:54,980 --> 00:30:56,460
We just do the usual thing.

775
00:30:56,740 --> 00:30:58,340
Let's just do the x component.

776
00:30:58,640 --> 00:31:00,120
Just do the x component.

777
00:31:00,120 --> 00:31:01,620
Let's not bother with the y component.

778
00:31:02,100 --> 00:31:03,660
We start with the x component

779
00:31:03,660 --> 00:31:04,920
and we first calculate

780
00:31:04,920 --> 00:31:08,260
the canonical momentum conjugate to x.

781
00:31:08,800 --> 00:31:10,880
That's the derivative of the Lagrangian

782
00:31:10,880 --> 00:31:12,320
with respect to x dot.

783
00:31:13,920 --> 00:31:14,440
So,

784
00:31:14,440 --> 00:31:15,400
p sub x

785
00:31:20,820 --> 00:31:22,180
p sub x

786
00:31:22,180 --> 00:31:24,760
is equal to the derivative of the Lagrangian

787
00:31:24,760 --> 00:31:25,860
with respect to x dot.

788
00:31:26,700 --> 00:31:28,020
That's m x dot.

789
00:31:28,020 --> 00:31:28,520
Well,

790
00:31:28,520 --> 00:31:29,620
that's not surprising.

791
00:31:30,040 --> 00:31:31,160
That's just m v.

792
00:31:32,500 --> 00:31:33,580
Good old momentum.

793
00:31:34,040 --> 00:31:35,420
But then there's another term.

794
00:31:38,160 --> 00:31:41,820
The x dot also appears in a dot v.

795
00:31:42,260 --> 00:31:44,860
This is x dot times a sub x.

796
00:31:45,120 --> 00:31:46,220
So there's another term.

797
00:31:46,600 --> 00:31:50,340
q a sub x.

798
00:31:50,540 --> 00:31:51,080
And that's it.

799
00:31:51,200 --> 00:31:52,740
q times a sub x.

800
00:31:53,620 --> 00:31:55,060
So we see something odd.

801
00:31:56,120 --> 00:31:57,880
That the canonical momentum

802
00:31:59,100 --> 00:32:01,920
is equal to the thing we usually call momentum,

803
00:32:02,160 --> 00:32:02,620
m v,

804
00:32:02,960 --> 00:32:05,780
plus an extra term which depends on the vector potential.

805
00:32:06,620 --> 00:32:07,840
But this is strange

806
00:32:07,840 --> 00:32:09,540
because the extra term

807
00:32:09,540 --> 00:32:11,740
is itself not gauge invariant.

808
00:32:11,740 --> 00:32:13,200
It depends on the vector potential.

809
00:32:13,580 --> 00:32:15,320
If I change the vector potential

810
00:32:15,320 --> 00:32:16,880
by adding something to it,

811
00:32:16,960 --> 00:32:18,200
I will change the momentum.

812
00:32:18,840 --> 00:32:19,400
Well,

813
00:32:19,400 --> 00:32:19,900
that's okay.

814
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:21,040
We follow the mathematics.

815
00:32:21,480 --> 00:32:23,460
If the mathematics tells us to do it,

816
00:32:23,460 --> 00:32:23,900
we do it.

817
00:32:24,260 --> 00:32:25,740
The canonical momentum

818
00:32:25,740 --> 00:32:27,720
of a point particle

819
00:32:28,020 --> 00:32:29,060
in a magnetic field

820
00:32:29,060 --> 00:32:31,020
is not gauge invariant.

821
00:32:31,440 --> 00:32:34,120
It means it's not a thing you really measure.

822
00:32:34,300 --> 00:32:36,260
It depends on your choice of the vector.

823
00:32:36,320 --> 00:32:37,460
We're going to give some examples

824
00:32:37,460 --> 00:32:39,320
of different choices of vector potentials

825
00:32:39,320 --> 00:32:40,360
and see how the whole thing works.

826
00:32:41,080 --> 00:32:43,120
But this is the canonical momentum.

827
00:32:43,300 --> 00:32:44,440
Now what's the equation of motion?

828
00:32:44,800 --> 00:32:46,420
The equation of motion is that

829
00:32:46,420 --> 00:32:47,980
the time derivative of this,

830
00:32:48,780 --> 00:32:50,440
the derivative of p x

831
00:32:51,180 --> 00:32:52,400
with respect to t,

832
00:32:53,780 --> 00:32:56,520
is equal to the derivative

833
00:32:56,520 --> 00:32:58,000
of the time derivative of this.

834
00:32:58,020 --> 00:33:00,040
Now this is just Lagrange's equations.

835
00:33:00,480 --> 00:33:01,400
d by dl,

836
00:33:01,400 --> 00:33:02,580
let's write it down,

837
00:33:03,840 --> 00:33:05,320
derivative of Lagrangian

838
00:33:05,320 --> 00:33:06,820
with respect to x dot

839
00:33:07,460 --> 00:33:08,480
d by dt,

840
00:33:10,200 --> 00:33:11,820
that's just the derivative of p,

841
00:33:12,060 --> 00:33:14,660
is equal to partial of l

842
00:33:15,240 --> 00:33:16,480
with respect to x.

843
00:33:18,040 --> 00:33:18,580
Well,

844
00:33:18,580 --> 00:33:19,740
the left-hand side

845
00:33:19,740 --> 00:33:21,620
is just the time derivative of this.

846
00:33:22,080 --> 00:33:25,360
So we can write m x double dot

847
00:33:29,220 --> 00:33:32,020
that's the first term of d by dt,

848
00:33:32,280 --> 00:33:33,240
d l dx dot,

849
00:33:33,400 --> 00:33:35,980
and then the second term is plus q

850
00:33:37,540 --> 00:33:39,660
times the time derivative of a sub x.

851
00:33:40,380 --> 00:33:42,020
I told you that a sub x

852
00:33:42,020 --> 00:33:43,440
was not a function of time.

853
00:33:43,660 --> 00:33:45,560
Does that mean that it doesn't depend on time?

854
00:33:46,320 --> 00:33:46,780
No.

855
00:33:47,540 --> 00:33:50,700
What it means is it doesn't depend explicitly on time.

856
00:33:50,760 --> 00:33:51,140
Here's the point.

857
00:33:51,740 --> 00:33:53,560
You may have a field in space

858
00:33:53,560 --> 00:33:55,860
which varies in space

859
00:33:55,860 --> 00:33:57,340
but does not vary in time.

860
00:33:57,980 --> 00:33:59,860
It doesn't vary in time at all.

861
00:33:59,920 --> 00:34:00,800
It's just something,

862
00:34:00,880 --> 00:34:02,880
some spatially dependent thing.

863
00:34:03,160 --> 00:34:04,940
But if a particle moves through it,

864
00:34:05,080 --> 00:34:07,640
then by virtue of the motion of the particle

865
00:34:07,640 --> 00:34:08,719
from point to point,

866
00:34:08,880 --> 00:34:10,980
the field at the particle

867
00:34:10,980 --> 00:34:12,440
